1.

That inference is much stronger than the evidence supports.

What your files support is this: **χριστός** has an old Greek pharmaceutical background, but by the 1st century its dominant Jewish and Christian meaning is no longer “drug/salve”; it is **“anointed one”** as a scriptural and messianic title. The project’s own summary says the classical uses are “pharmaceutical vocabulary with zero religious resonance,” while the LXX and NT stages show progressive narrowing from topical substance → priest/king title → expected deliverer → Jesus specifically.  

So two things can both be true:

The word’s **etymological basement** is smear/anoint language, including salves. 
But in Jesus-era usage, **Χριστός** is functioning as **Messiah-title**, not as a wink toward ointment practice. John 1:41 explicitly glosses it that way: **Μεσσίας = ὁ Χριστός**. 

And the leap from “old salve sense exists in the history of the word” to “Jesus was christing his eyes and rectal orifices for Bacchic altered states” is not justified by the material here. None of the attached evidence points to that practice, and the semantic trajectory in your notes points the other direction: the word is being **resemanticized upward into title and theology**, not dragged back into live drug slang. 

Best cautious formulation:

**Jesus may have lived in a bilingual, Hellenized environment where the root sense “anoint/smear” was not totally dead, but there is no evidence here that “Christ” functioned in his circle as coded drug language, much less as a reference to psychoactive salve use.**

2.

Your source stack is strongest when it does **three limited things**, and weakest when it tries to make the **final leap to Jesus**.

Strongest: it shows that Greek **φαρμακον** is genuinely polysemous — medicine, poison, charm, dye — and that Greek literature preserves a deep tradition linking drugs, ritual, death, reversal, and initiation. On that point, the report is well-built: Homer, Medea/Circe, Plato, Theophrastus, Dioscorides, Mithridates, and Galen do give you a real **Greek pharmacological-religious continuum**.   

Also strong: the report correctly notices that **χρίω / χριστός** belongs at root to the world of **smearing/anointing**, and that in medical writers anointing language can describe applying substances to bodies. That is a legitimate lexical observation. 

Where it weakens is in moving from **background plausibility** to **historical claim**. The existence of Greek mystery drugs, ritual anointing, narcotics, or death-and-return motifs does **not by itself** show Jesus knew, enacted, or encoded them. Your own earlier files actually push the semantics of **χριστός** toward LXX/Jewish title-language, not toward live drug slang in the 1st century. By the NT period, the dominant sense is “anointed one / Messiah,” even if the physical root is still there.

So the best scholarly formulation is:

**You have strong evidence for a Graeco-Roman pharmacological substrate and a real lexical overlap between anointing and substance-application. You do not yet have strong evidence that Jesus consciously positioned himself inside a Medea-to-mystery-cult chemical lineage. That remains an interpretive hypothesis, not a demonstrated conclusion.**

The best next move is to separate your case into two claims:

**Claim A: demonstrable** — Greek culture had a robust ritual-pharmacological tradition into the Roman period.
**Claim B: possible but unproven** — Jesus or his followers intentionally drew on that tradition.

That separation will make the project much harder to dismiss.

3.

A defensible path is not “prove it from wordplay,” but **build a cumulative case from practice, text, material culture, and context**.

Start with what you can actually show. Greek culture before and during Jesus had a real **pharmakon world**: Homer, Circe/Medea, Eleusinian and Bacchic material, Plato, Theophrastus, later Galen. Your file documents that broad substrate well.   

Then isolate **possible Jesus-adjacent drug evidence**:
Mark 15:23, Matthew 27:34, and John 19:29–30 on myrrhed wine / gall / sour wine; burial myrrh and aloe in John 19:39–40; anointing scenes; healing with saliva and mud. Your source already argues these are the strongest NT contact points.  

What would count as real proof:
an explicit ancient source saying Jesus or his circle used intoxicants, sedatives, entheogens, or ritual drugs; a hostile witness making the same claim; or archaeological/medical evidence tied directly to his movement.

What does **not** prove it:
the old pharmaceutical sense of **χριστός**. Your own files show that by the NT its dominant meaning is **Messiah / anointed one**, not live drug slang.   

So the best conclusion is: **there is a strong Graeco-Roman pharmacological background and a few suggestive gospel contact points, but no direct proof yet that Jesus used drugs.**
